<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-27T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-27T11:00:00-05:00" n="262" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00 Congress, Communist International,
                            VII/86: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-27T19:00:00+03:00">August 27,
                                    1935—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received August 27—1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>394. My No. 393. Careful perusal of <persName corresp="#p_KNN1">Krestinski</persName>’s note leads me to recommend that the
                            measures suggested in my numbers 363 to 369 of August 21<note n="64a" xml:id="d262fn64a">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_244">p.
                                244</ref>.</note> should be put into effect without delay.</p>
                        <p>I venture to suggest that if the President should touch the question of
                            the connection between the Soviet Government and the Communist
                            International he should state clearly the simple fact that both the
                            Soviet Government and the Communist International are merely different
                            aspects of <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s mind and
                            will.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>